r of =0Amagnitude as the average return from the IPO itself to T+4 over our=
 sample of =0A25%. ...=0A=0AOur estimate of average expected buying by CRSP=
-tracking index funds is 7% of =0Athe recently IPOed firm=E2=80=99s shares =
outstanding. This is an economically huge =0Ademand shock, larger than the =
net buying by index funds after e.g., Russell or =0AS&P Index family additi=
ons.=0A=0AOne odd point here is that the authors find both effects: The IPO=
 raises more =0Amoney at higher prices if everyone knows that index investo=
rs will show up in =0Afive days,and the stock trades up over those five day=
s. The IPO process reacts =0Ato the looming presence of index funds, but it=
 underreacts.=0A=0A=0AThe Trading Game=0A=0AI enjoyed (and blurbed) The Tra=
