 that you=E2=80=99ve heard of do.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footn=
ote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !i=
mportant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"=
> <span>[7]</span> </a>)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So very loosely sp=
eaking the total stock market index fund buys =E2=80=9Call of the investabl=
e stocks,=E2=80=9D but when a stock first=C2=A0<em>becomes </em>investable,=
 the fund doesn=E2=80=99t immediately buy it: It either waits until the nex=
t quarter to buy it, or =E2=80=94=C2=A0for a fast-track IPO =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
it waits five days to buy it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a =
private company thinking about an initial public offering, you will have to=
 find investors to buy your stock in the IPO. Most of those investors will =
be institutional investors who listen to your story, decide they like it an=
d put in an order. Others will be retail investors whose financial advisers=
 get them into the deal. But if you are big enough for the CRSP fast track,=
 then=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>of your IPO investors will be CRSP index inve=
stors (basically Vanguard=C2=A0funds). Oh, not really: You won=E2=80=99t be=
 in the index for five days after the IPO, so the index funds won=E2=80=99t=
 actually put orders into the IPO. But their demand for shares is so predic=
table that=C2=A0<em>somebody=C2=A0</em>will buy in the IPO=C2=A0<em>to flip=
 to them</em>, and then the stock will trade up a bit after the IPO, becaus=
e of that bump of index demand. Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://links.mes=
sage.bloomberg.com/u/click=3F_t=3Df574328d4d0c4c359b90d8e49b10e21d&_m=3Dac3=
37fbcc04940a3b48d56e8677851c5&_e=3DL97WGWRyAX9IJ9RxnxJB9kdaaIiAMGEVk2PDzOYF=
i7PWCK2GK9tPHsj_TFT96l0Ve2HcvMR0m8ySoaDLNqY5KtxxDA9HWX3iweG2TPUAVZwuOKhSywj=
